One possiblity would be to use [`reduceRight`][1] to &quot;reduce&quot; the `marks` sub-array of your input content to a single object with the required &quot;nested structure&quot;.

The idea is to start the reduction with the `{ type : &quot;text&quot;, text : content.text }` object (that will be nested), and then incrementally &quot;wrap&quot; that object with objects that contain the &quot;type&quot; data. 

To achieve the correct order of &quot;wrapping&quot; for objects with the type metadata, the `marks` array needs to be reduced in reverse. This is why  [`reduceRight`][1] is used (rather than regular [`reduce`][2]).

Here&#39;s an example snippet to show this idea in action:

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    /* Helper function processes the content object, returns the required
    nested structure */
    const processContent = ({ marks, text }) =&gt; 
        marks.reduceRight((acc, mark) =&gt; ({ type: mark.type, content: [acc] 
    }), {
      type: &quot;text&quot;,
      text: text
    });

    console.log(processContent({
      &quot;type&quot;: &quot;text&quot;,
      &quot;marks&quot;: [{
        &quot;type&quot;: &quot;bold&quot;
      }, {
        &quot;type&quot;: &quot;italic&quot;
      }],
      &quot;text&quot;: &quot;Testing&quot;
    }))

    /*
    Result:
    {
      &quot;type&quot; : &quot;bold&quot;, 
       &quot;content&quot; : [{ 
           &quot;type&quot; : &quot;italic&quot;, 
           &quot;content&quot;:[{ 
                &quot;type&quot; : &quot;text&quot;, 
                &quot;text&quot; : &quot;Testing&quot;
           }]
       }]
    }
    */

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

Hope that helps!


